    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-05-17T12:21:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-05-17T12:21:00-05:00" n="164"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d164">
                <head>164. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d164fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 493.119/5–1757. Secret; <gloss target="#t_niact1">Niact</gloss>;
                        Presidential Handling.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-05-17T13:21:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 17, 1957—1:21 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>8070. Please deliver following from President to <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Macmillan</persName>: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Dear <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Harold</persName>: <persName
                                corresp="#p_DJF1">Foster</persName> has just been talking to me
                            about the China trade situation and the message which he is sending to
                                <persName corresp="#p_LS1">Selwyn Lloyd</persName>
                            <note n="2" xml:id="d164fn2">
                                <ref target="#d165">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>
                                </ref>.</note> in reply to <persName corresp="#p_LS1"
                                >SELWYN</persName>’s memorandum which he gave to <persName>Jock
                                Whitney</persName> on the evening of May 13th.<note n="3"
                                xml:id="d164fn3">See <ref target="#d160">Document 160</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Our military advisers are strongly of the opinion that many of the items
                            which you would take off the China list will in fact appreciably help
                            the Chinese Communists to build up the military potential which
                            threatens us in this area and which we have the primary responsibility
                            to resist. Our Congress, although less well informed on the technical
                            details, feels strongly on this issue. As <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                                >Foster</persName> is saying to <persName corresp="#p_LS1"
                                >SELWYN</persName> we do not feel confident that increasing the list
                            will really help your trade very much. May it not mean merely that
                            China’s trade with you will consist of the more strategic rather than
                            the less strategic items?</p>
                        <p>We are, however, giving some new discretion to our representatives in
                            Paris and hope very much that you will try to meet us as it would be
                            unfortunate in many respects if we should split publicly on this
                            issue.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully yours, D.E.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Please observe Presidential Handling.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
